node.text: Eileen Mockus, CEO of sustainable homeware company @Coyuchi, talks with @archdigestpro editor @katy_magic about how to make your home more sustainable by making a few simple design choices.

node.title: In Conversation: Eileen Mockus, CEO of @coyuchi

node.accessibility_caption: Photo by Architectural Digest on July 20, 2021. May be an image of furniture and indoor.

node.text:
“When you go to the Champs-Élysées in Paris and you walk toward the Hermès or Louis Vuitton [store], the façade is very old and classical,” explains Shashi Reddy, the homeowner of this Atlanta home. “But after you enter, the space has this wonderful lighting, these very clean lines, and the antiquated feeling goes away. That’s what we were looking for in our home—we wanted the space to fit the neighborhood but to have interiors that matched our personalities.”

Tour the home at our bio link. Photo by @mali_azima; design by @joelkellydesign and @wyethrayinteriors; lighting design by @orsmandesign; words by @iamnickmafi.

node.accessibility_caption: Photo by Architectural Digest on July 19, 2021. May be an image of furniture and living room.

node.text:
It all started with a piano and a chance encounter in Paris. “The apartment has been in the family since the late 1970s,” the Beirut-born inhabitant explains of her abode, which is located not far from the Arc de Triomphe. “The previous owner had this piano and said, ‘If you want the apartment, you have to take the piano,’ since he didn’t want to move it out. It then became the starting point for everything [that followed].”

Tour this historic Parisian apartment at our bio link. Photo by @nicolas4matheus; design by @benoitdupuisarchitectes; words by @gaygassmann.

node.accessibility_caption: Photo by Architectural Digest on July 19, 2021. May be an image of sofa and living room.

node.text:
The breathtaking mountain landscape outside this home in Montana was conducive to creating a warm environment rich in textures and natural materials. “The neutral tones of stone, leather, and wood were just automatically the right answer,” interior designer Roger Higgins (@rhigginsinteriors) recalls of how he formulated his initial design scheme, which leans a bit toward the cool and contemporary while eschewing a “gimmicky Southwestern mountain lodge” aesthetic.

Tour the mountainside home at our bio link. Photo by @haris.kenjar; design by @rhigginsinteriors; words by Eric Allen.

node.accessibility_caption: Photo by Architectural Digest on July 19, 2021. May be an image of table.

node.text:
For @nateberkus and @jeremiahbrent's latest project , huge pocketing glass sliders erase the boundary between this inside and out in dramatic style, giving the home the feeling of an alfresco modernist pavilion. “When my dad visited, his big comment was ‘Your house has no walls,’ ” owner Brian Robbins recalls, laughing. Architect Paul McClean (@mccleandesign) buoyed the pavilion effect by overlapping the primary bedroom and the pool, so that the bedroom appears to float.

See the home Brent and Berkus designed for them at our bio link. Photo by @trevortondro; styling by @colinking; design by @nateberkus and @jeremiahbrent; architecture by @mccleandesign; words by @mayer.rus.

node.accessibility_caption: Photo by Architectural Digest on July 18, 2021. May be an image of outdoors.

node.text:
To make better use of the difficult hillside site of @falloutboy lead guitarist Joe Trohman and wife @marie.trohman's home, @proem_studio enlisted architects Peggy Hsu and Chris McCullough of the L.A. firm @hsumccullough, whose scope of work included a new pool—a daunting task that required caissons and piles between 80 and 100 feet long—a pool house, and a stairway-porch connector to ease the transition between the main house and the freshly pioneered outdoor playland. “The forms and materials of the new additions, the tile roof and arches of the pool house, the iron balustrade and harlequin tile of the stair, work within the existing language of the house,” Hsu explains.

Tour the beautiful home in Los Feliz at our bio link. Photo by Dan Arnold; design by @proem_studio; words by @mayer.rus.

node.accessibility_caption: Photo by Architectural Digest on July 18, 2021. May be an image of sofa and living room.

node.text:
Around this West Village house, blue-chip art and design mixes effortlessly with custom-made upholstered pieces and lots and lots of high-impact marble. The client was involved in all of it—“I had her go to the upholsterer,” explains #AD100 interior designer Julie Hillman (@juliehillmandesign). “We wanted her to sit on everything to know exactly what she was getting.”

Step into the incredible, art-filled spaces at our bio link. Photo by @manoloyllera; design by @juliehillmandesign; architecture by @stevenharrisarchitects; words by @_h_mart_.

node.accessibility_caption: Photo by Architectural Digest on July 18, 2021. May be an image of indoor.

node.text:
As the pavilion of this historic home in Hudson Valley was taking shape, homeowner David Ren was both delighted and slightly concerned about the surviving house: Even though design firm @workstead was spiffing up that interior, why would anyone want to use its 4,000 square feet when the forthcoming addition promised to be so appealing? In a now-familiar pattern, he expanded Workstead’s remit, and the studio began overseeing a near-total reconstruction of the artifact.

Tour the Victorian at our bio link. Photo by @matthewwilliamson; design by @workstead; styling by @mieketenhave; words by David Sokol.

node.text:
Entering through @taylor_hill's front door—a pop of red on the otherwise classic cabin construction—visitors land in a cozy living room featuring exposed log-and-mortar walls, original oak floors, and a fireplace surrounded by a stacked stone mantle. “I call it the Ralph Lauren room because it reminds me of Ralph’s Telluride house,” she says. “I’ve never been, but I’m obsessed with it.”

See more from AD's first digital cover at our bio link. Photo by @alyssarosenheck; styled by @alyssarosenheck; words by @libbycallaway1970.

node.text:
“We wanted a conversation between old and new, and to feel this high level of craftsmanship,” says designer Ryan Mahoney, noting that the woodwork of this Brooklyn home's kitchen wraps around the original brick fireplace to the new mudroom. A similar degree of precision went into the primary suite, where adjoining rooms were absorbed to realize a dressing area and vast, wood-paneled bath with a freestanding tub, shower, sauna, and separate toilet room.

Read the web-exclusive home tour at our bio link. Photo by Matthew Williams; design by @workstead; words by @samuelcochran.

“We worked very closely with [@milesredd and @davidkaihoi] to set it up for their decoration,” says Peter Pennoyer (@peterpennoyerarchitects), architect behind this Ohio family home. Amazingly, it was also the first time he and Redd had worked together. “To me it was such a logical pairing,” says the client. “Peter’s proportions allow Miles’s decorating to shine, and Miles’s colors highlight Peter’s architecture.”

Tour the Ohio home at our bio link. Photo by Ryan Kurtz; styled by Jessie Cundiff; design by @reddkaihoi; words by @janekeltnerdev.

node.text:
In order to balance the typically limited natural light found in town homes, designer Fawn Galli (@fawngalliinteriors) bleached the herringbone floors of her Brooklyn home and added luminous materials such as silks and metallics. Her favorite part of the structure is the yellow stained glass window that casts a sunny glow across one hall and, at just the right time, this dining room.

Tour her home at our bio link. Photo by @jeffholt; design by @fawngalliinteriors; architecture by @scalar_architecture; words by @christianelemieux.

In the L.A. house of @mileycyrus, tiger face Gucci wallpaper was the inspiration for a powder room’s design. “Miley had told me that when you’re in this bathroom, it should be an experience,” says Miley's mom and designer @tishcyrus. “I was a little scared, but we went all in. When we put the finishing touches of the horsehair sconces in, it was like, Wow, it works and it’s awesome.”

Tour the whole home at our bio link. Photo by @jennapeffley; design by @tishcyrus and @thematfinish; words by @arielfoxman.
